<h1>About Sway</h1>

<p>Sway, the innovative and efficient subway system, has been serving the bustling cityscape since its grand opening in 2023. As we embark on the year 2046, Sway has evolved into a comprehensive network of lines that seamlessly connect various parts of the city.</p>

<h2>Key Information</h2>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Name:</strong> Sway</li>
    <li><strong>First Opened:</strong> 2023</li>
    <li><strong>Current Year:</strong> 2046</li>
    <li><strong>Line count:</strong> 11</li>
    <li><strong>Station count:</strong> 145</li>
</ul>

<h2>Lines</h2>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Line A:</strong> The first line, boasting many old designs.</li>
    <li><strong>Line B:</strong> The second line, featuring the shortest and the longest tunnels.</li>
    <li><strong>Line C:</strong> Originally just two stations, it has evolved into one of the longest lines with two branches.</li>
    <li><strong>Line D:</strong> The shortest line with an uncertain future.</li>
    <li><strong>Line E:</strong> A short light line facilitating quick travel.</li>
    <li><strong>Line F:</strong> Home to the deepest stations, currently undergoing expansion towards the far South.</li>
    <li><strong>Line G:</strong> A circular urban rail line, nearing completion.</li>
    <li><strong>Line H:</strong> A fairly modern line traversing the city center.</li>
    <li><strong>Line I:</strong> An urban rail line connecting the North to the South.</li>
    <li><strong>Line J:</strong> An underground circular line, still in the construction phase.</li>
    <li><strong>Line K:</strong> An urban rail line extending to the West.</li>
</ul>
